Therefore, according to Konig's theorem, the minimum vertex cover is 4. But how can that be? If we take 4 squares, how can they cover all possible dominoes? Let's try to construct such a set. Suppose we take the four squares: (1,1), (1,2), (2,3), (3,3). Let's check coverage: - Domino (1,1)-(1,2): covered by (1,1) and (1,2) - Domino (1,2)-(2,2): (1,2) is covered, (2,2) not in the set - Domino (2,2)-(2,3): (2,3) is in the set - Domino (2,3)-(3,3): covered by (2,3) and (3,3) - Domino (3,3)-(3,2): (3,3) is covered, (3,2) not in the set - Domino (3,2)-(3,1): (3,2) not covered - Domino (3,1)-(2,1): (3,1) not covered, (2,1) not in the set - Domino (2,1)-(1,1): covered by (1,1) and (2,1) - Domino (1,3)-(2,3): (2,3) is covered - Domino (2,2)-(1,2): (1,2) is covered - Domino (2,1)-(3,1): (3,1) not covered - Domino (1,1)-(2,
